key_points: Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department obtained a search warrant for the black box from Tiger Woods' crashed car.
Sheriff's department does not seek a warrant for Woods' blood to determine if he was under the influence.
A warrant for the black box requires probable cause that a crime was committed.
Deputy John Schloegl emphasized the investigation is part of routine probe, not necessarily indicating a criminal investigation.
The black box data could provide details on the vehicle's speed, steering, brake, and acceleration before the crash.
In 2017, Woods was found asleep at the wheel with various medications in his system.
No evidence of impairment was observed in Woods immediately after the crash.
Accident reconstruction experts suggest Woods may not have been paying attention, possibly asleep at the wheel.
Sheriff Alex Villanueva initially called the crash "purely an accident," but the department has not concluded the cause.
Genesis, the car's manufacturer, has taken possession of the vehicle after the sheriff's department completed its examination.
